message.raw:
Added check for NI PCIe 6363 to ensure that the current version of NI-DAQmx is not 14.0.

NI-DAQmx v14.0 seems to have a bug where the Digital Output task raises the following exception: "DAQError: Finite acquisition or generation has been stopped before the requested number of samples were acquired or generated."

Other versions of NI-DAQmx don't seem to have this issue, and neither does the NI PCI 6733 even when using DAQmx v14.0.

The issue is resolved using NI DAQmx v14.2 or higher (also tested as working with v9.2.3)

message.raw:
Restores previous symmetric clock pulses as the default behaviour for the PulseBlaster (fixes #16)

Also fixes issues with:
 * long delay instructions (the number of reps must be at least 2)
 * calculation of when to use a long delay instruction when using assymetric clock pulses
 * assymetric clock pulses don't make sense if it isn't used as a pseudoclock (now raises LabscriptError)

message.raw:
Updated NI PCI 6733 device to add features and fix bugs

 * Added manual control of PFI flags
 * Fixed bugs in BLACS worker process preventing use of digital outputs in experiments
 * Fixed bug in labscript code which demanded an even number of child devices, not an even number of AnalogOuts
 * Fixed bug in labscript code which had the incorrect dtype for the digital output numpy array. This caused an obscure "index out of range" error in a bitfield conversion.

message.raw:
Workaround for a bug in NI DAQmx. Added a property to the NI_DAQmx class
to enable the workaround. This flag instructs the wait monitor subprocess
to skip the first rising edge detected (on other devices this edge is not
detected in the first place), and it instructs labscript code to generate an
0.1 second pulse for the wait monitor instead of a shorter pulse. This bug has
been observed on the NI usb 6229 and NI DAQmx 15.0

message.raw:
Workaround for problem where spurious PulseBlaster falling edges caused
the novatech to advance its table, despite not being in table mode.

The workaround has it transition to table mode and back again, before going into
table mode for a buffered run. This "double clutch" mechanism appears to reset
its memory pointer to the start of the table. There may still be a potential race
condition in which the PulseBlaster gives its pulses after the double-clutch.
If so, A fix for this might entail imposing an ordering on the devices transitioning
to buffered.

This was because the change to the pseudoclock/clockline object hierarchy in labscript requires an extra method to be defined in the tab class as outputs are now more removed from the device the tab belongs to.

Updated novatech to use connection_table properties as it should.
Added a new option "default_baud_rate" which when set tells labscript that
the novatech will start with that baud rate and should be return to it when
shut down.  We accept the possibility that the baud rate is already set, so
errors in setting the baud rate are ignored.

message.raw:
NI_DAQ_MX acquisition reports bugs to Paco.  Labscript is setup to do AI's
differently from how we did them in labview.  It sets up a buffer and reads
it out once it is filled and then waits for more data, rather than reading it
out in one get-go like we do with labview.

For now, I have increased the buffer size to match what NI suggests.
